 tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the resistance to the violence of gender-based oppression, vibrant – but often ignored – worlds have emerged, full of nuance, humour, and beauty. Correcting an absence of writing about contemporary feminist work by Canadian artists, Desire Change considers the resurgence of feminist art, thought, and practice in the past decade by examining artworks that respond to themes of diversity and desire.Essays by historians, artists, and curators present an overview of a range of artistic practices including performance, installation, video, textiles, and photography. Contributors address the desire for change through three central frames: how feminist art has significantly contributed to the complex understanding of gender as it intersects with sexuality and race; the necessary critique of patriarchy and institutions as they relate to colonization within the Canadian nation-state; and the ways in which contemporary critiques are formed and expressed.Heavily illustrated with representative works, Desire Change raises both the stakes and the concerns of contemporary feminist art, with an understanding that feminism is always and necessarily plural.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArtzCanadaxHistory. 0aFeminism and artzCanada. 0aFeminism in art. 0aFeminist art criticismzCanada. 0aWomen artistszCanada. 0aWomen in art. 7aART / History / General.2bisacsh1 aAnderson, Janice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBadger, Gina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBancroft, Marian Penner, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Lorna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBr